title: Tea Mug with Tea bag holder for left and right handed drinkers

description.text:
I got tired of our enginerds walking around with a teacup and soggy tea bag, so I sought out a cup with an intgrated tea bag holder. Not finding one, I designed this one using Spaceclaim and saved the model as an .STL file. There is a left handed version for left handed users and a right hand version for the rest of us.
It printed just fine on our Stratasys Dimension 1200 SST. It's very strong in solid infill, but with sparse infill it prints faster and keeps the contents hotter longer. It is still plenty strong for its intended purpose.
Use as a hot beverage holder at your own risk. Designer takes no responsibility for injury caused by dumping hot products on the user, bystanders, pets, animals, zombies, attorneys or politicians.

Ok, so I printed it this morning. It does work, and it does fit. But, it is a little wonky. If I try to get it to seat properly (flat to the lens so nothing can get into the lens area) I have to press while pushing which allows the inner tension ring to come loose. I spent some time looking and comparing with my other 77mm cap (17-49L) and saw that the ridges that lock the cap to the inner ring were much thinner, like the equivalent of 2 or 3 layers. I printed at .20 mm / layer.
It could be too, that this is a different lens cap, and it will just take some getting used to.
As to the file, perhaps some point soon.
I am not using Sketchup at the moment. I have been doing mostly CNC with my shapeoko, and am just moving into the 3D printing side of things. Most of my CNC work has been 2.5 D and I have been using Draftsight. I have downloaded Fusion 360 and have started playing with that, but am only just coming up to speed on the true 3D modeling. description.text:
No more loss of belt tension on your X Belt with your one/Two/Three up Or any thing that requires a NEMA 17 Footprint to attach a belt to. The files here allow for the swap over to an easily replaceable, Open ended, GT2 belt.
Check the link below for images to see how the tensioner works. A spring tensioner can still be used as long as it doesn't interfere with the path of travel. As for the Carriage, I used one of the more popular designs, and trimmed a little off of the back side to ensure everything fits. With the carriage removed, install your new open ended belt around the Idler and pulley.
Slip the belt into the clamp and Secure it. Ensure it is tight with very little slack.
Next, set the carriage on the bearings and align the belt clamp with the carriage. Pass your screws through them and build your extruder. I Borrowed this design, After I saw it i fell in love, Awesome clamp.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:587659 UPDATE
Added a V2 belt clamp, When I was assembling mine, I managed to Break one of the belt keepers off. The new design allows for a bit more rigidity. I suggest printing either of them with a High infill and/or More shells/Perimeters. UPDATE
The box on the clamp was too big and would contact the belt. Updated to V3. Also, I noticed that if you use too long of a screw in the mount, it will catch the edge of the belt as it travels.

title: Stops warping of ABS & Nylon prints, Enjoy it!

description.text:
After a bit of experimenting, I have found what I believe to be the very best, most consistent method to stop warping of ABS & Nylon ( possibly other plastics.) I use Blue Painters Tape on heatbed, then brush on a thin layer of Elmers Washable Clear School Glue. In my opinion it provides the perfect adhesion properties. ABS and Nylon both stick great to it (even if your bed is not perfectly level!). Equally impressive is the fact that when you remove the print, it will pop off without excessive effort. I can promise you will not be sorry trying this. I tried the glue on kapton tape originally,l which worked well, but not as good as on the blue tape. If you try it on bare glass, please tell me your results. I haven't tried it simply because currently the blue tape and glue is working so good.. and I suppose sometimes i'm lazy ;)
You can dry it faster by heating Print Bed to 45 degrees.

Its good to hear that others are already making use of various types of Elmer's glue on their print beds. I did recently hear of glue sticks being recommended for Nylon. Otherwise, I didn't think very many people knew about it or were trying it with other plastics. I was planning on trying this without heating the bed (w/ABS), so thanks for sharing srPowdercoating! My only concern with the bed heated is with large prints and uneven heating. I just want to point out that the different types of glues you all mention, do have some differences in their properties. For instance the clear type I use has less ingredients and additives, with a makeup closer to that of Polyvinyl Alcohol vs the other types of washable Elmer's glue. awhile back I did a bunch of comparisons and testing diff. Elmers glue looking for the one most like actual PVA. Here are some of the advantages of the clear type of glue I use. Its consistency is thinner, enough to spread around easily and bond into the blue tape (helps the blue tape stay down, being stiffened with infused glue.) Also, it is much more water soluble (a wet finger more easily fix it, if it flakes anywhere, after maybe removing a very large print.) Even if you all are happy with the results from your current type of glue, give this type a try and see what I'm talking about!

IMPORTANT!!!
The Parts in this Project Need alot of after edit. Its not hard, but needs some time.
The Sound is ok, but not Very loud. i Just Wanted to make something diffrent than all
the other Projects i saw on the Make it Loud Challange. Watch how it works and how to build it here:
https://youtu.be/Pdawiz793NY No Parts were Glued together, just plugged together.
the Original Color Was Red and White (i run out of white Filament for Prototype parts)
I Sprayed all the Parts with some spray. The Spray is made for Cars, but it works for this aswell. Its easiest to Print it in the right Color from the Beginning. This is my first Project on Thingiverse i designed on my own. im very Proud on it, cause i never learned things like this professionel. teached all i know myself. I hope their criticism is not too hard ;D

Notes: Whole Project was Printed with ABS
Not Every Part Need Support.
Here The parts i Printed with Support:
  • Arm left
  • Arm Right
  • Head
  • Shaft
  • Hammer
  • Gear Propulsion
    • Some Parts need to be Printed twice:
  • Hammer
  • Fixation

Final Product I Started Designing The Gears, and find a good position for them so they can move smoothly.
After i had the Gears i made the Pillars, and thought more about the Whole Gear system. I wanted to make it simple, easy to print, but still effective. The 2 Drums were 1 big Drum at start, but i changed it to two smaller Drums. The Walls were just to hold it all in position, and the Head was just a plate with some slots to hold the walls togehter.
The Next step was to find out a system for the Arms, so he can drum. Just a Stick would make it stuck, so i had to figure out a way the hammer folds back after Hitting the Drum.
So i designed this how it actually is. If you rotate the handle fast enought the Hammer´s are getting more speed and Hit the Drums with more Power for Louder sound. At last i Thought i can make a Robot out of it. The Head was added, and to let it look more like a robot i added some details on the Front Wall.

Printing Tips There are alot of small Parts That need some time To cool down before the Printer sets the next layer on it. if you print only 1 small part the printer finished 1 layer, starts the next layer before it is cooled down, and the print will fail. here i got some pictures for you as a example how you can print it. Only Big parts, you can print them single or together The Drums, the Bottom and the 2 Fixations. i Put them on this plate, because they will get enought cooldown time here. This are all small Parts which need Support material. The Head can also be printed in a single print

rear anchors, carbon fibre plugs, keyboard flips, v2 Add-on

Parts needed and Assembly Parts needed: 2 x M3 20mm screws
2 x M3 16mm screws
12 x M3 8mm screws
4 x 10mm springs
8 x 10mm (diameter) washers (about 0.5mm thickness)
2 x 200mm carbon fibre rods (10mm diameter)
2 x 146mm carbon fibre rods (10mm diameter) — I cut down from 200mm with a dremel cutter
2 x anti-slip stick-on padding (optional) All parts, except the rear anchors, carbon fibre plugs and keyboard flips, need to be printed with support Prints needed: 1 of each except 6 x CR rod plug Assembly:
  • Insert 1 x 200mm carbon fibre (CF) rod into the front of either Holder (the one with a through hole)
  • Insert 1 x CF rod plug, align with edge
  • Drill 3/4 way through M3 pilot hole, CF rod and the plug with a 1.8mm drill bit
  • Lock with 1 x M3 8mm screw
  • Insert 2 x Keyboard Flips into that rod, follow orientation of pictures
  • Insert 1 x CF rod into rear receptacle of the Holder
  • Insert 2 x CF rod Rear Anchors into that rear CF rod. Note: Install the looser fitting sides, this allows for sliding.
  • Insert both CF rods into / through the other Holder. Then repeat Steps 1 thru 4 with the other holder
  • Install Left or right arm to the respective holder with this combination: washer - spring - washer (M3 20mm screw through that assembly. Screw through Arm unit, into Holder. Tighten to the tension you prefer. Caution: Over-tightening makes it a pain to operate, under-tensioning makes the assembly weak
  • Repeat for other holder
  • Insert 146mm CF rod through one arm, add corresponding Leg Base Clamp over end of CF rod. Insert CF rod plug, repeat drill through and M3 screw installation. Repeat for other side.
  • Install Leg Flaps, follow step 9, but use M3 16mm screws (Caution: Do not over tighten, there is only 3mm of wall in the Leg Base Clamp, exceeding that could damage your CF rod)
  • Repeat drill through and M3 screw installation with the rear anchors.
  • Add anti-slip padding as desired.
  • Add v2 add-on to left and right holder with 2 M38mm screws each, then insert the rod and attach the locking clip with 1 M38mm screw each side.

This file is uploaded here as-is with no warranty of any kind, either express or implied. This object is a 20mm diameter cylinder. It's intended to be used as a calibration print to ensure different FFF printers produce very similar cylindrical prints. We use it by: 1.Changing the print settings appropriately for the filament that is to be used.
2.Slicing at 100% infill with the print settings that are intended to be used for the final cylindrical print.
3.Measuring the result with calipers, ensuring the diameter is 20mm +/- 0.5mm (ideally +/- 0.3mm).
4a.If it is, we're done with the cal.
4b.If it's not, adjust extrusion settings or gantry's squareness (or equivalent). The extrusion settings should be changed appropriately if the diameter is consistently greater or less than 20mm. The gantry's squareness (or equivalent) should be adjusted if the diameter varies by more than 1mm (ideally < 0.6mm).

description.text:
This is Yet Another Hexagonal Heated Bed Holder, but with a twist: I've designed it keeping in mind that some versions of the hexagonal heated bed available on the web have the solder plates near the mounting holes or need soldered components to be placed in the middle of the sides, making other mounts unusable. This version uses the free holes at the vertices to keep the bed in place; on top of these holes a triangle holds the glass in place as well. You'll need to print the following pieces:
  • 4x Glass Holders
  • 4x Bed Holders (choose between the M3x15 and M3x20 versions)
    • And you'll need the following parts to fix the supports to the aluminium beams:
  • 4x M3x15 / M3x20 screws
  • 4x M3 screws (any reasonably short length)
  • 4x M3 bolts
  • 4x Slightly larger washers to avoid the bolts sliding out of aluminium beams.
    • See the post-printing section for more instructions.

• Push an M3 bolt in its slot under the bed holder.
  • Push the M3x15/M3x20 screw in the wider hole of the bed holder.
    • If you chose the M3x20 version, push the screw through the slimmer squared piece as well - it has been separated from the upper plate only to simplify printing.
  • Slide the washer and bolt on the screw.
    • The final assembly should look like this:

Slide the supports inside the aluminium beams and screw the triangle-shaped glass holders in the smaller holes (the ones with the bolt on the underside), through the bed holes.

description.text:
I'm buying filament in 1kg spools, but my printer holds 0.5kg spools, so I always have to rewind the filament from one spool to another. It isn't convenient nor fast. So here is my solution. Adapter fits on the regular hexagonal drill bit, the rest speaks for itself. Use adapter to hold and spin one spool, and your imagination how to hold another spool.
This particular adapter works for both spools that came with FlashForgeDreamer2. It may not work for you as there are too many kinds of spools out there, but it may give you an idea for your own creations.

The desk where my 3d printer sits is getting pretty cluttered, and space is at a premium.  I'm constantly picking this roll of tape up and moving it around, so I thought I'd give it a better home, and designed this holder.
The first draft of the design was sort of a fixed bar that just went straight out.  I didn't even bother printing that one, because I'm 100% positive I would have gotten sick of running into it when the tape wasn't on there, so I redesigned it with a hinge.  Now, when the tape is in use, or I've left it somewhere else, I can move the holder out of the way.
